# USNM experiments

Code base for the preparation and execution of USNM experiments

## Installation

- Download and install [Git](https://git-scm.com/download)
- Open a terminal and enter your git credentials:
```
git config user.name "<Your Name>"
git config user.email "<your@email>"
```
- Download and install an [Anaconda](https://www.anaconda.com/products/individual) Python distribution
- Open the Anaconda prompt and create a new `usnmexps` Anaconda environment with **Python 3.6**:
```
conda create -n usnmexps python=3.6
```
- Activate the new conda environment:
```
conda activate usnmexps
```
- Move to the directory where you want to store your code base
- Clone this repository:
```
git clone https://github.com/shohamlab/usnmexps.git
```
- Move to that directory and install the code base as an editable python package: 
```
cd usnmexps
pip install -e .
```
- Create a new configuration file called `config.py` and save it in the `usnmexps` subfolder. Inside this file, define 3 Python variables:
    - `CHECK_ENV`: a boolean variable that determines whether to check the anaconda environment before running a script
    - `CALIBRATION_DATA_FOLDER`: the path to the calibration data folder
    - `MAPPING_DATA_FOLDER`: the path to the mapping data folder
    - `PROTOCOLS_FOLDER`: the path to the protocols folder (for USNM imaging experiments)
- *Optional*: if you want to make changes to the code base, download and install a Python editor, e.g. [Visual Studio Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/)

## Update

If you are updating the code base to a new version:
- Open a terminal and move to the `usnmexps` folder
- Pull the latest version from the repository:
```
git pull
```
- Update `instrulink` package dependency:
```
pip install --upgrade instrulink
```

## Usage

All user scripts are located in the `/scripts` subfolder. These scripts all come with optional command line options. To see the available options, run a script with the `-h` flag:
```
cd scripts
python <name_of_script>.py -h
```

